Explore CNV distributions of reference cells: SCPCP000015

Stephanie J. Spielman

2025-05-28

Introduction

We have previously observed that the reference cell CNV distributions in pooled references may overlap with tumor CNV distributions. This notebook aims to explore the extent of this trend for SCPCP000015.

Functions

prepare_cnv_df <- function(infercnv_tsv) {
  
  infercnv_df <- readr::read_tsv(infercnv_tsv)

  infercnv_metadata_df <- infercnv_df |>
    dplyr::select(
      -starts_with("has_"),
      -starts_with("proportion_"),
      -starts_with("top_")
    ) |>
    dplyr::mutate(cell_group = stringr::str_split_i(subcluster, "_", 1)) 
  
  infercnv_df |>
    tidyr::pivot_longer(
      starts_with("has_cnv_"),
      names_to = "chr",
      values_to = "cnv"
    ) |>
    # sum all values for each
    dplyr::group_by(cell_id) |>
    dplyr::summarize(total_cnv_per_cell = sum(cnv)) |>
    dplyr::ungroup() |>
    # bring back metadata
    dplyr::inner_join(
      infercnv_metadata_df,
      by = "cell_id"
    ) 
}

result_dir <- file.path(module_dir, "results", "SCPCP000015") # organized as sample/reference/infercnv results
ewings_dir <- file.path(repository_base, "data", "current", "results", "cell-type-ewings", "SCPCP000015")

Input files

# inferCNV output files
infercnv_files <- list.files(
  path = result_dir, 
  pattern = "_cnv-metadata\\.tsv",
  recursive = TRUE, 
  full.names = TRUE
) |>
  # remove any containing "endo_immune" or "internal"; we only want pooled endo or immune
  purrr::discard(\(x) {stringr::str_detect(x, "endo-immune|internal")}) |>
  # name by "library-reference"
  purrr::set_names(\(x) {
    library_id <- stringr::str_split_i(basename(x), "_", 1)
  })

# ewing module cell types
celltype_files <- list.files(
  ewings_dir,
  pattern = "_ewing-celltype-assignments\\.tsv",  
  recursive = TRUE, 
  full.names = TRUE

  # name by library id
  purrr::set_names(\(x) {stringr::str_split_i(basename(x), "_", 1)})

Read input files

Well first read in the cell type annotations:

celltype_df <- celltype_files |>
  purrr::map(readr::read_tsv) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "library_id") |>
  dplyr::mutate(cell_id = glue::glue("{library_id}-{barcodes}")) |>
  dplyr::select(cell_id, consensus_annotation, ewing_annotation)

Now, well read in the inferCNV results:

infercnv_df <- infercnv_files |>
  purrr::map(prepare_cnv_df) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "infercnv_library_id") |>
  dplyr::inner_join(celltype_df, by = "cell_id") |>
  # condense labels for cell type groupings
  dplyr::mutate(
    label = ifelse(
      stringr::str_detect(ewing_annotation, "tumor"), 
      "tumor", 
      cell_group
    ), 
    label = forcats::fct_relevel(label, "unknown", "tumor", "reference")
  )

Analysis

Well first visualize the total CNV distributions for each inference for each grouping of cells:

  • unknown: query cells
  • tumor: query cells labeled tumor by cell-type-ewings
  • reference: cells in the normal reference
immune_df <- infercnv_df |>
  dplyr::filter(normal_reference == "immune_pooled")

endo_df <- infercnv_df |>
  dplyr::filter(normal_reference == "endo_pooled")

ggplot(immune_df) +
  aes(x = total_cnv_per_cell, y = label, fill = label) +
  ggridges::geom_density_ridges2(scale = 0.9) +
  facet_wrap(vars(infercnv_library_id)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  ggtitle("Immune pooled reference")



ggplot(endo_df) +
  aes(x = total_cnv_per_cell, y = label, fill = label) +
  ggridges::geom_density_ridges2(scale = 0.9) +
  facet_wrap(vars(infercnv_library_id)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  ggtitle("Endo pooled reference")

  • The endo reference cell CNV distributions generally do not overlap with tumor cell CNV distributions.
  • The immune reference cell CNV distributions do have a wider spread but do not substantially overlap with the tumor cell CNV distributions.

Lets look more closely at the immune reference to see if any particular libraries might be driving a (minor) trend. For each inference with the pooled immune reference, well find the 25% top reference cells with the highest CNVs. Do these cells tend to be from a particular library?

First, note how many reference cells come from each library:

ref_immune_df <- immune_df |>
  dplyr::filter(cell_group == "reference") |>
  tidyr::separate(cell_id, into = c("reference_library_id", "barcode"), sep = "-", remove = FALSE)


ref_immune_df |>
  dplyr::select(cell_id) |>
  dplyr::distinct() |>
  tidyr::separate(cell_id, into = c("reference_library_id", "barcode"), sep = "-") |>
  dplyr::count(reference_library_id)

The table displayed below shows for each inference (infercnv_library_id), how many of top 25% CNV cells in the pooled immune reference are from each library. For example, of the reference cells with the highest CNVs in the SCPCL000822 inference, 28 cells came from SCPCL000822, 30 cells came from SCPCL000824, etc. Generally, these numbers are consistent across inferences although cells from SCPCL000824 do seem to be more prevalent in certain samples. Even so, there doesnt seem to be any major trend here.

top25 <- ref_immune_df |>
  dplyr::group_by(infercnv_library_id) |>
  dplyr::slice_max(total_cnv_per_cell, prop=0.25) |>
  dplyr::ungroup()
top25 |>
  dplyr::count(infercnv_library_id, reference_library_id) |>
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = reference_library_id, 
    values_from = n, 
    values_fill = 0
  )
